Swarm versus kubernetes.

It helps to see the two side by side. On installation, swarm is a single command with zero extra software, while kubernetes means a cluster bootstrap tool, a managed cloud service, or several binaries, and it is genuinely non-trivial to stand up. On the client, swarm uses the same docker command you already know, while kubernetes uses an entirely separate tool and model. On concepts, swarm has a handful, service, task, stack, secret, and config, while kubernetes has dozens, pods, deployments, replica-sets, services, ingresses, config-maps, persistent volumes, and many more.

The pattern continues across the board. Swarm has built-in overlay networking and a routing mesh that just work, while kubernetes makes networking your choice among plugins. Swarm does rolling updates with rollback, while kubernetes adds blue-green, canary, and controllers for everything. Swarm's ecosystem is small and mostly docker-shipped, while kubernetes has a vast ecosystem of charts, operators, and service meshes. And swarm is mature and mostly stable, while kubernetes evolves rapidly. Importantly, both run the same open-container-initiative images, so the image you built in notebook two deploys identically on either.

So when is each right. Swarm is the right answer when you want orchestration without the kubernetes complexity tax, for small teams, edge and internet-of-things clusters, and simple production, and it is what the certification exam tests. Kubernetes is the right answer when you need its ecosystem, when you are going multi-cluster, or when you are hiring at scale into a talent pool that knows it. Most large companies are on kubernetes today, but learning swarm is not wasted time, because the concepts, declarative state, rolling updates, secrets, placement, carry over directly. Kubernetes is, in a sense, swarm but bigger and with more knobs, so starting here makes the bigger system far easier to learn.
